TY  - JOUR
T1  - Ownership Structure and Firm Profitability in Japan
AU  - Gedajlovic, Eric
AU  - Shapiro, Daniel M.
Y1  - 2002/06/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069381
DO  - 10.5465/3069381
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 565
EP  - 575
VL  - 45
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examined the relationship between the ownership structure and financial performance of 334 Japanese corporations for the 1986?91 period. The positive relationship we found between ownership concentration and financial performance is consistent with agency theory predictions. In addition, we observed a more pronounced profit redistribution effect characterized by the transferring of financial resources from more to less profitable firms. These findings indicate the need to account for both economic incentives and social context in corporate governance research.
AB  - We examined the relationship between the ownership structure and financial performance of 334 Japanese corporations for the 1986?91 period. The positive relationship we found between ownership concentration and financial performance is consistent with agency theory predictions. In addition, we observed a more pronounced profit redistribution effect characterized by the transferring of financial resources from more to less profitable firms. These findings indicate the need to account for both economic incentives and social context in corporate governance research.
